Here's how you might write this Julia program:

```julia
using Statistics: mean, maximum, minimum

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (; average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    end

    avg = round(mean(temps), digits=2) # 2 decimal places
    max_temp = maximum(temps)
    min_temp = minimum(temps)

    if temps == fill(avg, length(temps))
        return (; average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:stable)
    elseif temps[1] < avg  # temperature list is decreasing
        return (; average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:decreasing)
    else
        return (; average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:increasing)
    end
end
```

This function first checks if the input list is empty. If it is, then it returns a named tuple with all values set to nothing.
If the list has elements, it computes the average temperature, the maximum and minimum temperatures, and determines the trend based on whether the daily temperature data is increasing or decreasing. It uses Julia's `Statistics` functions for mean, max, and min calculations. If all days had the same temperature (checked via equals), it declares it as "stable". Otherwise, if it was increasing or decreasing, it flags the trend accordingly.

Remember to run this piece of code in a Julia environment where Statistics package is already installed.
